1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,900
 Hello, and welcome to our continuing series of lectures

2
00:00:02,900 --> 00:00:07,800
 on improving our implementation of a Python object.

3
00:00:07,800 --> 00:00:11,100
 So what we've been doing is we have been building a series

4
00:00:11,100 --> 00:00:15,440
 of implementations, of approximate implementations,

5
00:00:15,440 --> 00:00:17,960
 some of the things that we find in Python,

6
00:00:17,960 --> 00:00:19,700
 like the Python dictionary.

7
00:00:19,700 --> 00:00:24,000
 And so the last thing we worked on was this Python dictionary class,

8
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:27,240
 and the previous implementation was just a linked list with a key.

9
00:00:28,240 --> 00:00:30,640
 Now, we're going to eventually have to build all kinds of different

10
00:00:30,640 --> 00:00:32,800
 implementations, and so the part of what we're doing

11
00:00:32,800 --> 00:00:37,700
 is we're working toward abstraction, where we're separating what the object

12
00:00:37,700 --> 00:00:40,640
 is that we're interacting with from how we build it underneath.

13
00:00:40,640 --> 00:00:45,340
 And so we're going to do things like move our methods into the structure

14
00:00:45,340 --> 00:00:48,360
 instead of just using prefix-style naming conventions,

15
00:00:48,360 --> 00:00:54,860
 and just reduce the need to look inside the class

16
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:58,840
 or inside the structure that is holding our class

17
00:00:58,840 --> 00:01:00,640
 for code that's in our calling code.

18
00:01:00,640 --> 00:01:07,960
 So we don't want to have to look at the class values inside the class.

19
00:01:07,960 --> 00:01:12,260
 So this is just continuing along understanding object-oriented principles.

20
00:01:12,260 --> 00:01:16,500
 The three principles of object orientations are encapsulation,

21
00:01:16,500 --> 00:01:19,260
 abstraction, inheritance, and polymorphism.

22
00:01:19,260 --> 00:01:23,300
 And so for now, we're bundling more things together.

23
00:01:23,440 --> 00:01:26,540
 That's encapsulation, and we're working on abstraction,

24
00:01:26,540 --> 00:01:33,200
 and that is thinking about separately how we are going to use this object

25
00:01:33,200 --> 00:01:35,260
 from how we're going to build the object.

26
00:01:35,260 --> 00:01:40,960
 We're going to reveal less and less of our implementation details to the caller.

27
00:01:40,960 --> 00:01:46,960
 And so for a while, we just said,

28
00:01:46,960 --> 00:01:52,000
 "Well, we'll just take the class and add an underscore and name it,"

29
00:01:52,140 --> 00:01:55,200
 et cetera, et cetera, and it seems absolutely simple enough.

30
00:01:55,200 --> 00:01:58,900
 And in some ways, you see that C++ does exactly that

31
00:01:58,900 --> 00:02:02,460
 when it's compiling C++ to C code.

32
00:02:02,460 --> 00:02:06,360
 But it seems like it's simple enough,

33
00:02:06,360 --> 00:02:07,740
 and it seems like you would keep it straight,

34
00:02:07,740 --> 00:02:10,000
 but it turns out to be a bad idea in practice.

35
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:13,860
 So Python strings, which I can write Python code

36
00:02:13,860 --> 00:02:15,840
 and not have to look up documentation,

37
00:02:15,840 --> 00:02:19,540
 are real objects that follow the principle of encapsulation.

38
00:02:19,660 --> 00:02:23,200
 Everything that you touch is inside of the object,

39
00:02:23,200 --> 00:02:26,500
 like uppercase, because searching for something.

40
00:02:26,500 --> 00:02:31,600
 PHP strings are kind of more archaic,

41
00:02:31,600 --> 00:02:35,540
 and that PHP is more of a C-like way of thinking about things,

42
00:02:35,540 --> 00:02:38,140
 and there are type, and then there's a bunch of libraries

43
00:02:38,140 --> 00:02:39,860
 that know how to use this type.

44
00:02:39,860 --> 00:02:44,000
 And so I'm going to show you some ickiness in PHP,

45
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:48,540
 but I do love PHP, so I'm not just criticizing PHP.

46
00:02:48,660 --> 00:02:50,040
 PHP has a lot going for it.

47
00:02:50,040 --> 00:02:54,340
 But in the language and the library, there are some annoyances.

48
00:02:54,340 --> 00:02:56,600
 So let's take a look at a little bit of Python

49
00:02:56,600 --> 00:02:58,160
 and some equivalent PHP.

50
00:02:58,160 --> 00:02:59,940
 And so you sort of see this notion

51
00:02:59,940 --> 00:03:03,240
 that naming convention seems tempting,

52
00:03:03,240 --> 00:03:05,060
 but it's not necessarily a great idea.

53
00:03:05,060 --> 00:03:09,360
 So in Python, we say x equals a string, we call x.find,

54
00:03:09,360 --> 00:03:12,740
 and it has the first parameter, the thing we're looking for.

55
00:03:12,740 --> 00:03:16,660
 And then we have y equals x.replace old new.

56
00:03:16,800 --> 00:03:19,660
 And so the first parameter is the old string,

57
00:03:19,660 --> 00:03:21,700
 and the second parameter is the new string.

58
00:03:21,700 --> 00:03:23,500
 And then we say how long this thing is.

59
00:03:23,500 --> 00:03:25,240
 And so everything's very consistent.

60
00:03:25,240 --> 00:03:28,560
 But if we look at PHP, it's almost identical,

61
00:03:28,560 --> 00:03:31,340
 except it's calling libraries, right?

62
00:03:31,340 --> 00:03:33,640
 So $x equals a string with old in it,

63
00:03:33,640 --> 00:03:36,360
 and then we're going to use stir pose.

64
00:03:36,360 --> 00:03:38,440
 That is the position in a string,

65
00:03:38,440 --> 00:03:41,040
 and the first parameter is what they call the haystack,

66
00:03:41,040 --> 00:03:44,300
 and then the second parameter is width, which we call the needle.

67
00:03:44,440 --> 00:03:48,040
 But then we look at the replacement, which is equivalent of x.replace

68
00:03:48,040 --> 00:03:52,840
 in Python, and it's not stir replace, it's stir_replace.

69
00:03:52,840 --> 00:03:56,700
 So do we use underscores or do we not use underscores?

70
00:03:56,700 --> 00:04:00,200
 And then the thing that just drives me crazy is what is the,

71
00:04:00,200 --> 00:04:02,640
 what would you expect the first, second,

72
00:04:02,640 --> 00:04:05,440
 and third parameter of PHP stir replace?

73
00:04:05,440 --> 00:04:11,240
 Well, if I was writing it, it would be the source string,

74
00:04:11,360 --> 00:04:15,240
 the old search string, and the new thing to replace it with.

75
00:04:15,240 --> 00:04:19,060
 But that's not what it is.

76
00:04:19,060 --> 00:04:22,160
 The stir_replace says old string, new string,

77
00:04:22,160 --> 00:04:25,160
 and then the string we're doing the searching in.

78
00:04:25,160 --> 00:04:30,440
 You can go look this up, but PHP talks about how there were generations

79
00:04:30,440 --> 00:04:33,860
 of things, like stir pose, I think, is one of the earlier ones.

80
00:04:33,860 --> 00:04:38,400
 Stirlen, basically, that's one of the older ones,

81
00:04:38,400 --> 00:04:40,060
 and so it's consistent with stir pose,

82
00:04:40,200 --> 00:04:42,260
 but not consistent with stir replace.

83
00:04:42,260 --> 00:04:45,400
 And so the naming conventions is just less than ideal,

84
00:04:45,400 --> 00:04:49,000
 and you can just see from a programmer understanding,

85
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:51,740
 it's just really simple that if we look at the Python,

86
00:04:51,740 --> 00:04:54,000
 it says y equals x.replace old new,

87
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:56,640
 I can remember that calling sequence,

88
00:04:56,640 --> 00:05:00,960
 and I can never remember the stir_replace in PHP.

89
00:05:00,960 --> 00:05:04,160
 So the thing we're going to do here

90
00:05:04,160 --> 00:05:06,660
 is we're going to put the methods in the structure,

91
00:05:06,660 --> 00:05:09,760
 and so we see some of our C code before and after,

92
00:05:10,600 --> 00:05:12,900
 and so we create a PyDict,

93
00:05:12,900 --> 00:05:17,140
 and then you'll notice that just like what PHP did,

94
00:05:17,140 --> 00:05:23,200
 I called those PyDict_put, PyDict_len, and PyDict_get.

95
00:05:23,200 --> 00:05:25,840
 I was consistent because I always used underscores,

96
00:05:25,840 --> 00:05:30,100
 and PyDict is the name of the structure, PyDict_del,

97
00:05:30,100 --> 00:05:32,300
 and so I was pretty consistent with that.

98
00:05:32,300 --> 00:05:35,040
 But now what we're going to do in the name of encapsulation

99
00:05:35,040 --> 00:05:38,560
 is we are going to take all those methods,

100
00:05:38,700 --> 00:05:40,540
 make them be part of the structure.

101
00:05:40,540 --> 00:05:42,700
 We're going to find that they're just pointers to the methods,

102
00:05:42,700 --> 00:05:44,760
 but we are going to have global methods.

103
00:05:44,760 --> 00:05:48,100
 We're just not going to access them through their global names.

104
00:05:48,100 --> 00:05:50,300
 So we're going to create a new PyDict,

105
00:05:50,300 --> 00:05:55,560
 saying PyDict_new, but then we're going to call to put something in,

106
00:05:55,560 --> 00:05:57,840
 we're going to call DCT arrow put,

107
00:05:57,840 --> 00:06:00,760
 and remember, we have to make this first parameter

108
00:06:00,760 --> 00:06:02,500
 like the self parameter DCT,

109
00:06:02,500 --> 00:06:04,860
 that's just always going to be that first parameter

110
00:06:04,860 --> 00:06:07,200
 because we're sort of doing it Python style,

111
00:06:07,340 --> 00:06:11,500
 and then you kind of know that Z is the key and catchphrase is the value.

112
00:06:11,500 --> 00:06:14,500
 And so that's the calling sequence.

113
00:06:14,500 --> 00:06:19,500
 And again, that DCT comma is just because we're not an object-oriented language,

114
00:06:19,500 --> 00:06:21,040
 and so we put self in there.

115
00:06:21,040 --> 00:06:25,240
 Again, homage back to exactly the way that Python did it

116
00:06:25,240 --> 00:06:26,800
 and why they did it the way they did it,

117
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:29,600
 because they were creating an object-oriented framework

118
00:06:29,600 --> 00:06:33,600
 on top of a non-object-oriented environment, just like we are.

119
00:06:33,600 --> 00:06:35,760
 And then you look at DCT arrow len,

120
00:06:36,440 --> 00:06:39,560
 and of course, putting DCT in as the first parameter is redundant,

121
00:06:39,560 --> 00:06:42,740
 but necessary, and we can do a DCT get,

122
00:06:42,740 --> 00:06:47,060
 and in effect, other than the first parameter, which is DCT,

123
00:06:47,060 --> 00:06:49,500
 we are putting the key in, and away it goes,

124
00:06:49,500 --> 00:06:51,540
 and then we could call the Dell method.

125
00:06:51,540 --> 00:06:55,360
 But now you'll notice that every single method

126
00:06:55,360 --> 00:06:59,140
 that is associated with a PyDict is in the PyDict structure.

127
00:06:59,140 --> 00:07:02,800
 So let's talk about how we're going to do that and why.

128
00:07:03,400 --> 00:07:07,640
 And so this all kind of falls under leaky abstractions,

129
00:07:07,640 --> 00:07:11,040
 meaning that when we're in the main calling code

130
00:07:11,040 --> 00:07:14,560
 and we sneak in and peek at the data attributes inside the class,

131
00:07:14,560 --> 00:07:15,960
 we call this leaking.

132
00:07:15,960 --> 00:07:18,960
 And later we'll talk about iterators and why we...

133
00:07:18,960 --> 00:07:21,660
 Iterators seem inconvenient and clunky,

134
00:07:21,660 --> 00:07:23,860
 but what their whole job really is,

135
00:07:23,860 --> 00:07:27,760
 is to hide implementation details to make it cleaner abstraction.

136
00:07:27,760 --> 00:07:31,660
 When the calling code depends on the internal implementation names

137
00:07:31,800 --> 00:07:35,040
 and approaches, that's what it is to be leaky.

138
00:07:35,040 --> 00:07:37,500
 So we need to define a contract between the class

139
00:07:37,500 --> 00:07:41,000
 and its calling code from above that we won't change.

140
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:43,360
 We're going to call this contract on interface.

141
00:07:43,360 --> 00:07:46,040
 Another kind of word for that is abstraction.

142
00:07:46,040 --> 00:07:52,060
 And so if we look at all the code in our earlier implementation,

143
00:07:52,060 --> 00:07:54,300
 the whole thing is leaky, right?

144
00:07:54,300 --> 00:07:58,200
 Especially if you look at that for loop where it says for struct

145
00:07:58,340 --> 00:08:02,200
 denode cur equals DCT arrow head, cur not equal null,

146
00:08:02,200 --> 00:08:06,400
 cur equals cur next, print cur key, and cur value.

147
00:08:06,400 --> 00:08:09,840
 And so what happens is, that should trigger a little like...

148
00:08:09,840 --> 00:08:13,860
 Eh, eh, eh, that says don't look inside these things.

149
00:08:13,860 --> 00:08:16,800
 And this is what we later we'll talk about iterators,

150
00:08:16,800 --> 00:08:19,000
 how far we go and how we actually...

151
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:21,500
 What we look at, this code that we're looking at right here,

152
00:08:21,500 --> 00:08:23,260
 I think it's pretty,

153
00:08:23,260 --> 00:08:25,600
 but it kind of violates the abstraction boundary

154
00:08:25,740 --> 00:08:28,660
 because we're looking too deeply into the fact

155
00:08:28,660 --> 00:08:30,340
 that this is even a linked list.

156
00:08:30,340 --> 00:08:32,860
 We don't know there's a linked list. It may not be a linked list.

157
00:08:32,860 --> 00:08:35,260
 It may be some other kind of a structure.

158
00:08:35,260 --> 00:08:36,900
 It may be a tree or whatever.

159
00:08:36,900 --> 00:08:38,900
 And we will later get to the point

160
00:08:38,900 --> 00:08:42,400
 where we will make these things different implementations,

161
00:08:42,400 --> 00:08:44,140
 not just a linked list.

162
00:08:44,140 --> 00:08:48,260
 And so that's this idea that you should be like,

163
00:08:48,260 --> 00:08:52,560
 "Oh no, there's this little wall, but now I'm looking inside."

164
00:08:52,560 --> 00:08:53,700
 And then when you're looking inside,

165
00:08:53,840 --> 00:08:56,160
 that's when you kind of are violating the abstraction boundary,

166
00:08:56,160 --> 00:08:58,400
 or we call it a leaky abstraction.

167
00:08:58,400 --> 00:09:02,960
 What this leads to is the notion of not all object attributes are the same.

168
00:09:02,960 --> 00:09:06,200
 And so when we're going to build an object,

169
00:09:06,200 --> 00:09:09,560
 we are going to decide what parts of these things are the contract

170
00:09:09,560 --> 00:09:13,240
 and what parts are leave us alone, we're going to hide this stuff.

171
00:09:13,240 --> 00:09:16,740
 And so the concepts in object-oriented programming

172
00:09:16,740 --> 00:09:19,700
 are that things that the calling code is allowed to see,

173
00:09:19,700 --> 00:09:22,760
 whether they be data or methods are called public.

174
00:09:23,560 --> 00:09:27,560
 Things that are like reserved for class use only are private.

175
00:09:27,560 --> 00:09:29,840
 And then when we start talking about inheritance,

176
00:09:29,840 --> 00:09:31,600
 which we won't talk about too much,

177
00:09:31,600 --> 00:09:34,100
 there is this middle class called protected.

178
00:09:34,100 --> 00:09:37,760
 And that is stuff that classes and derived classes can look at,

179
00:09:37,760 --> 00:09:40,460
 but not the calling code.

180
00:09:40,460 --> 00:09:43,860
 So protected is sort of more like private

181
00:09:43,860 --> 00:09:46,260
 from the point of view of calling code.

182
00:09:46,260 --> 00:09:48,860
 So if you look at the abstraction boundary that we have here,

183
00:09:48,860 --> 00:09:51,460
 we see that the place where the abstraction boundary

184
00:09:51,600 --> 00:09:55,960
 is sort of failing is that head and tail.

185
00:09:55,960 --> 00:10:01,040
 We want to make an abstraction boundary and say that look,

186
00:10:01,040 --> 00:10:05,000
 that the notion of head and the tail, that's going to be all ours

187
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:07,040
 and that's going to be all inside.

188
00:10:07,040 --> 00:10:09,760
 And that's inside the abstraction boundary

189
00:10:09,760 --> 00:10:12,360
 and you're not supposed to mess with it.

190
00:10:12,360 --> 00:10:17,100
 So we look at how we do this in Java, there is a keyword called private.

191
00:10:17,100 --> 00:10:19,400
 And so Java, we're making a point class

192
00:10:19,540 --> 00:10:22,960
 and we're making two double values that we're saying x and y are private,

193
00:10:22,960 --> 00:10:27,140
 which means you can't access it outside of this class.

194
00:10:27,140 --> 00:10:29,840
 The constructor is public and the dump is public.

195
00:10:29,840 --> 00:10:34,360
 And so you see that that just means that you can't access x and y

196
00:10:34,360 --> 00:10:38,360
 outside of the class, but you can access dump and the constructor.

197
00:10:38,360 --> 00:10:41,040
 In C++, you see a private and a public.

198
00:10:41,040 --> 00:10:43,160
 And so private says this double x and y

199
00:10:43,160 --> 00:10:45,040
 are things that can only be used inside the class

200
00:10:45,040 --> 00:10:48,800
 and public is the constructor can be used outside the class

201
00:10:48,940 --> 00:10:51,200
 and the dump can be used outside the class.

202
00:10:51,200 --> 00:10:54,040
 And this is just syntax that they put in.

203
00:10:54,040 --> 00:10:58,360
 Now, interestingly, access control in Python is a little sort of wonkier

204
00:10:58,360 --> 00:11:02,860
 because Python doesn't really put things like public and private.

205
00:11:02,860 --> 00:11:05,440
 So what Python is doing, and you've seen these

206
00:11:05,440 --> 00:11:06,900
 across all the Python you've done,

207
00:11:06,900 --> 00:11:10,660
 where you see these double underscores and dundas, as it were,

208
00:11:10,660 --> 00:11:12,600
 like the constructor, you're not supposed to call

209
00:11:12,600 --> 00:11:16,060
 the underscore underscore init underscore underscore.

210
00:11:16,200 --> 00:11:18,900
 That's just when you create an object, that's what happens.

211
00:11:18,900 --> 00:11:24,340
 And so the init is an internal method, it's a private method.

212
00:11:24,340 --> 00:11:26,840
 Underscore underscore x and underscore underscore y

213
00:11:26,840 --> 00:11:28,200
 are totally valid variable names,

214
00:11:28,200 --> 00:11:30,340
 except we're marking to the outside world,

215
00:11:30,340 --> 00:11:32,600
 hey, you're not supposed to access these.

216
00:11:32,600 --> 00:11:35,800
 And then def dump, the fact that we didn't put double underscore

217
00:11:35,800 --> 00:11:37,840
 in front of it means that it's public.

218
00:11:37,840 --> 00:11:43,260
 And so double underscore is the signal inside of Python to do access control.

219
00:11:43,260 --> 00:11:46,140
 And we look at some of the stuff that C++ really does,

220
00:11:46,260 --> 00:11:50,640
 this was borrowed in many ways from how C++ does things internally.

221
00:11:50,640 --> 00:11:55,140
 So up next, we're going to talk about this map and the abstraction

222
00:11:55,140 --> 00:11:58,040
 and the kinds of things that we do under the covers

223
00:11:58,040 --> 00:12:00,240
 of the implementation details of the abstraction.

224
00:12:16,200 --> 00:12:21,200
 [MUSIC]

